Most Kenyans are hardwired to equate Christmas with consumerism: from drinking alcohol to shopping to partying, you name it.Relatives, too, often feel entitled to money and goodies from their kin. This year’s norm-shattering Christmas will be the ultimate antidote for the hedonism that accompanies the holiday each time. Most Kenyans are hardwired to equate Christmas with consumerism: from drinking alcohol to shopping to partying, you name it.
Retailers have always cashed in on the "Christmas Spirit" over the years, and overzealous but unscrupulous preachers have taken advantage of the season, shouting themselves hoarse from the pulpit, repeating the phrase: “It’s the season for giving!” until their pockets fill up.



