Given such trends, the definition of the "Christmas Spirit" definitely depends on whom you ask. But let's go back to the basics for a bit.
Humility and modesty
Christmas is a celebration of the birth of Jesus. When Jesus was born, his mother Mary placed him in a manger “because there was no place for them in the inn". It doesn't take a doctorate in theology to retrieve the lesson on humility and modesty here. And why the excessive celebrations people indulge in during the Christmas season is a contrast to some of the values Jesus espoused.
Amid a worsening Covid-19 pandemic, some Kenyans are travelling to their villages to celebrate Christmas with their loved ones, treating the holiday as they have always had: a chance to imbibe drinks and eat copious amounts of food.
Only that this time, they might also be bringing Covid-19 along with them. We can only pray that they will wear their masks, sanitise and keep their social distance. And that they will be future case studies on how all that can be achieved while eating, drinking and making merry.



